## What Happened

**`DSA` was marked obsolete (`SYSLIB0042`) in .NET 7**, and Microsoft has been progressively removing platform support. On macOS, the runtime relied on an OpenSSL interop shim for DSA since Apple's native crypto frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) dropped DSA long ago.

In .NET 11, that last fallback path on macOS was removed, so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.

## How to Fix

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not generate new ones), use **BouncyCastle**:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)
{
    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);
    signer.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is a managed (portable) implementation—no platform crypto dependency, works identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS.

## Long-term

Migrate callers to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** for new signatures and treat DSA verification as a legacy compatibility path only.
